                    <note>
                        <date type="foundation" from="1733" to="1746">1733-1746</date>
                        <desc type="foundation">This church was founded by <roleName type="title">ʾǝtege</roleName>
                            <persName ref="PRS2682BerhanM">Mǝntǝwwāb</persName> over a period of
                                <date dur="P13Y">13 years</date>: she began the process in <date when="1733">1733</date>, dedicated the tābot in <date>1740</date>,
                            completed the building around <date when="1743" precision="low">1743</date> and completed the church's endowment sometime <date notBefore="1746">after 1746</date>.</desc>
                        <ab type="history">After its foundation by <roleName type="title">ʾǝtege</roleName>
                            <persName ref="PRS2682BerhanM">Mǝntǝwwāb</persName>, Dabra Ḍaḥay Qʷǝsqʷām became one of the
                            most important churches of Gondar. However, it was sacked by <roleName type="title">ʾaṣe</roleName>
                            <persName ref="PRS9430Tewodros">Tewodros II</persName> in <date when="1866">1866</date>. He removed many of its manuscripts that
                            ended up in the <placeName ref="INS0001BL">British Library</placeName>.
                            The church was sacked even further by the Mahdists in the <date from="1880" to="1890">1880s</date> and seriously damaged by air
                            strikes in <date when="1941">1941</date>. Although it was recently
                            restored, it lost its past glory.</ab>
                        <ab type="description">Dabra Ḍaḥay Qʷǝsqʷām is a church in the north-western part of
                                <placeName ref="LOC3577Gondar">Gondar</placeName> and close to
                                <placeName ref="LOC6540Entone">ʾAbbā ʾƎnṭonǝs</placeName>. It was
                            one of the most important churches of the town and richly endowed with
                            lands in <placeName ref="LOC1712Bajana">Bāǧanā</placeName>, <placeName ref="LOC1739Balasa">Balasā</placeName> and in <placeName ref="LOC2767Ebenna">ʾƎbǝnnāt</placeName> that supported 260
                            clergy.</ab>
                    </note>
